<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONRAD'S JERUSALEM CARTOON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Conrad either has not bothered to read your paper's news reports or has chosen 
to create his own facts upon which to base his false and misleading cartoon. As 
reported in these pages, approximately 150 Jewish settlers moved into a 
building in Jerusalem's Jewish quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Contrary to Conrad's depiction, the building was not the site of the Last 
Supper, nor is it a holy site at all. No places holy of any faith were violated 
in any way by the act of the settlers. 
</P>
<P>
When Jordan seized the Old City of Jerusalem during the 1948 Arab-Israeli war, 
all Jewish inhabitants were expelled and denied access to the Western Wall and 
Jewish holy places; edifices and cemeteries were desecrated. 
</P>
<P>
Israel reunited Jerusalem after the 1967 war and the Israeli government passed 
the Protection of Holy Places law guaranteeing the preservation of all holy 
sites in the city in accordance with Israeli law which protects the freedom of 
religion and worship for people of all faiths. 
</P>
<P>
The settlers broke no law in their actions; any illegality relates to the issue 
of tenancy and subtenancy. Israel's Supreme Court has upheld the eviction of 
the settlers and ordered that they must leave the site. 
</P>
<P>
While the settlers and the Israeli Housing Ministry were rightfully condemned 
for their insensitivity, this was not and should not be wrongfully portrayed as 
an Israeli attempt to conquer the holy sites of any other faith. Conrad's 
placement of Prime Minister Shamir and an Israeli flag on the table of Da 
Vinci's Last Supper is inaccurate and is not based on the facts as they were 
reported by The Times. 
</P>
<P>
TZIVIA SCHWARTZ 
</P>
<P>
Associate Western States Counsel 
</P>
<P>
Anti-Defamation League 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
