<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL BASEBALL ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
BETTER THAN AVERAGE: SANDERS RALLIES POWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN HENDERSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Poway's Matt Sanders entered Friday's Palomar League showdown with Mt. Carmel 
batting .056, but it was his three-run home run that sparked a 10-9 upset over 
the No. 2 Sundevils. 
</P>
<P>
Sanders was the team's designated hitter only because senior Frank Wolinski 
came down with the flu Friday morning. Coincidentally, Sanders had hit a 
three-run homer in Thursday's practice to give the juniors a 6-5 victory over 
the seniors. 
</P>
<P>
But his drive over the left field fence in the third inning was for real and 
breathed new life into Poway, which needed some quick resuscitation after Mt. 
Carmel's six-run third inning. 
</P>
<P>
The Sundevils had taken a 7-1 lead into the bottom of the inning but entered 
the fourth still in a game, 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
A big third-inning defensive play by right fielder Greg Sorrell also helped the 
Titans win. Sorrell threw out Andy Owen at home to end Mt. Carmel's six-run 
rally. Owen was trying to score from second on John Moon's single, the eighth 
hit of the inning for the Sundevils. 
</P>
<P>
That one run made the difference. 
</P>
<P>
The victory went to reliever Danny Miller (9-1), who pitched the sixth and 
seventh innings. He struck out three and got an exceptional defensive effort 
from first baseman Robbie Plarski with runners on first and second to end it. 
Moon and Andy Panganiban were aboard on infield hits when Plarski reached over 
the six-foot fence up to his elbow and snared Armando Sanchez's foul ball for 
the final out. 
</P>
<P>
Plarski also doubled off the fence in the fourth inning to drive home a run 
that cut Mt. Carmel's lead to 9-7, then drove home the game-winner in the sixth 
with a double to right center field. 
</P>
<P>
The winning rally began with Sorrell's walk and a wild pitch by loser Todd 
Voigt (0-1). Matt Schwenke followed with his third single, which scored Sorrell 
to tie it at 9-9, then went to second on the throw home. Plarski broke the tie. 
</P>
<P>
The victory pulled No. 10 Poway (15-6-1, 6-3) and Rancho Buena Vista within two 
games of Mt. Carmel (19-4, 9-1) and virtually assured the Titans a playoff 
spot. 
</P>
<P>
In other Palomar games: 
</P>
<P>
Vista 5, Fallbrook 4 -- Chris Adams and Jason Harrington combined on a 
four-hitter to lead Vista 10-12-1, 4-5-1. Fallbrook is 9-11, 4-6. 
</P>
<P>
Orange Glen 3, Torrey Pines 0 -- Jim Roby hit a two-run homer, and Scott 
Campbell pitched a four-hitter for Orange Glen (15-9, 6-4). Shaw Henderson 
allowed five hits for Torrey Pines (10-14, 1-9). 
</P>
<P>
Rancho Buena Vista 10, San Dieguito 1 -- Chris Gorr was three for three, George 
Hadden three for four and Dave Roberts two for three with three RBIs and three 
stolen bases for Rancho Buena Vista (12-10-1, 7-3). The Longhorns' Donovan 
Crocker (5-5) had nine strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
Avocado League 
</P>
<P>
Oceanside 10, Carlsbad 2 -- Oceanside (19-7, 7-2) maintained its half-game 
league lead with the victory at home. The Pirates benefited from nine walks, a 
hit batsman and three Carlsbad errors. Bill Precht (4-2) came on with two out 
in the fourth and gave up just two hits for the victory. Jose Avila hit a 
bases-empty home run in the second for Oceanside. 
</P>
<P>
San Pasqual 12, El Camino 6 -- Marin Soto (three for three) and Eric Marsh 
(three for four) led a 14-hit attack for San Pasqual (9-10-1, 6-2). Bobby 
Womble homered for El Camino (10-12, 4-5). 
</P>
<P>
Escondido 4, Ramona 1 -- Brian Klungreseter (5-2) pitched a six-hitter, and Tom 
Afenir went two for three with an RBI and run scored for Escondido (11-10., 
6-3). 
</P>
<P>
Grossmont 2-A League 
</P>
<P>
Grossmont 18, Valhalla 9 -- John Tatum had his second two-homer game of the 
season in an 18-hit attack for No. 1 Grossmont (22-2, 5-0). Tatum, who had two 
home runs in the same inning last week, was three for four with four RBIs. Mike 
Spears (6-0) went four innings for the victory. Jim Early added a three-run 
homer, Greg Layson was three for four with two RBIs and Jason Eskridge three 
for three with two runs for the first-place Foothillers. Tavo Carrillo was two 
for three with four RBIs for Valhalla (12-12-1, 2-3). 
</P>
<P>
El Cajon Valley 7, West Hills 2 -- Mike Stadler pitched a five-hitter for El 
Cajon Valley (7-12, 2-3). West Hills is 3-19, 0-5. 
</P>
<P>
Grossmont 3-A League 
</P>
<P>
El Capitan 16, Mount Miguel 4 -- Jason Reed (3-5) struck out eight in six 
innings, and reliever Mike Farrell went three for five with two doubles and two 
RBIs for El Capitan (17-7, 5-0). Mount Miguel committed eight of the game's 14 
errors. 
</P>
<P>
Nonleague 
</P>
<P>
San Marcos 7, Clairemont 6 -- San Marcos (12-9) scored seven runs in the third 
inning. MARTIN HENDERSON 
</P>
