<HEADLINE>
<P>
REVIEW ATTACKS YOUTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Randy Lewis' article on comedians Sam Kinison and Andrew (Dice) Clay ("Hate 
Mongers Are a Bad Chapter in the History of Comedy," April 22) was an 
opinionated, narrow-minded, malicious attack on not only these comedians but 
also the youth of America. 
</P>
<P>
Just because he doesn't like their style of comedy, that does not give him the 
right to condemn those who do. 
</P>
<P>
The young people of America are not "imbecilic" or "easily brainwashed" into 
following a persona (as the older generation was when they supported Reagan's 
supply-side economics). We are just into something else, something different. 
Every generation is different from the next; it's been like that in the past 
and will continue to be like that in the future! 
</P>
<P>
So, Mr. Lewis, I am sorry if my generation does not idolize your Woody Allen or 
Lenny Bruce (as you would like). But you cannot ignore change or "pray that it 
will go away," because it will not (whether you like it or not). 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL GRUBBS, Fullerton 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050590-0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 214373 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 5, 1990, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 3; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
472 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
REMOVING LENNON PHOTO FROM EXHIBIT A HUGE MISTAKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like a mythological Hydra -- cut off one head and two more grow -- censorship 
is increasing apace. The most recent local example (at least in appearance but 
contradicted by a museum spokeswoman) is the removal, and subsequent return, of 
a photo depicting a naked, fetal-curled John Lennon lying next to a clothed 
Yoko Ono, which had been selected for an art exhibit at the Muckenthaler 
Cultural Center in Fullerton. ("Nude Photo of Lennon Removed in Fullerton," 
April 25.) 
</P>
<P>
While I am indifferent toward the photo itself, and whether the cultural center 
displays it or not, I am concerned about the museum trustees' usurped decision 
of "perceived community concerns," which led to the photo's removal. 
</P>
<P>
I am also disturbed about the local arts community's silence, except for a few 
perfunctory squeaks. 
</P>
<P>
Where were the public comments from Orange County's artists, performers and 
writers? The dearth of reaction from professionals, arts organizations and 
museums only serves to reinforce the "little ado in Orange County" attitude 
that accompanied a recent Times article about the lack of local response to the 
controversy surrounding artistic content and funding for the National Endowment 
for the Arts. 
</P>
<P>
In contrast to arts organizations across the United States that are picking up 
the gauntlet against the encroachment of subtle restrictions and outright 
censorship, members of Orange County's arts community were quoted as being "too 
busy," among other things, to be actively involved in the issue. 
</P>
<P>
Can we afford the portent of such complacency? 
</P>
<P>
No. Waiting until we aren't too busy (which never happens), or until we have a 
reason to act (i.e., when we are finally directly affected by censorship) is 
dangerous and shortsighted. 
</P>
<P>
Dangerous because our apathy allows others to make choices for us. Shortsighted 
because through our inaction we have permitted the self-appointed monitors of 
morality and taste to lay a foundation for future restraints in other areas of 
our lives. 
</P>
<P>
Tacit approval clings to silence that is maintained in the face of decisions 
made by "guardians" of what we will see, hear or read. 
</P>
<P>
The point has been made more than once in recent months that as the countries 
of Eastern Europe and Latin America approach greater freedom of movement and 
free expression, we in the United States are, paradoxically, tightening 
(through evermore refined means) the restrictions on our own rights. 
</P>
<P>
The incidents at the Muckenthaler Cultural Center reflect more than just the 
removal of a photograph in a moment of poor judgment. It mirrors growing forces 
that are determined to curtail personal choice, and not just in the arts. 
</P>
<P>
We should all be more aware and more engaged in issues affecting our right to 
exercise freedom of choice. If not us, who? If not now, when? 
</P>
<P>
JANET E. GRAEBNER, Santa Ana 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050590-0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 214374 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 5, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
