<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH'S SON TO TESTIFY ABOUT THRIFT FAILURE; 
</P>
<P>
S&amp;LS: LOANS TO NEIL BUSH'S BUSINESS PARTNERS WHILE HE WAS ON THE BOARD OF A 
COLORADO THRIFT WERE ALLEGEDLY A CONFLICT OF INTEREST. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Neil Bush, the president's son, said Friday that he has agreed to testify 
before the House Banking Committee about the failure of a Colorado thrift on 
whose board he served. 
</P>
<P>
The panel, chaired by Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez (D-Tex.), is looking into the 
December, 1988, collapse of Silverado Banking, Savings &amp; Loan Assn. of 
Denver. 
</P>
<P>
The connections among Silverado and other failed S&amp;Ls are being examined, 
including Charles H. Keating Jr.'s Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Assn. and the 
junk bond operation of former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. financier Michael 
Milken. 
</P>
<P>
The committee has scheduled two hearings. Thrift regulators are expected to 
testify May 22; Bush and other Silverado board members are to appear May 23. 
</P>
<P>
"I have agreed to participate and will continue to cooperate with Congress, the 
Office of Thrift Supervision and any other agencies involved," Bush said in a 
statement released through his attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
The thrift office has alleged that loans by Silverado to Bush's business 
partners, developers Kenneth Good and Bill Walters, were a conflict of interest 
for Bush. 
</P>
<P>
Neil Bush was on the S&amp;L's board from October, 1985, until August, 1988. 
</P>
<P>
In January, regulators began disciplinary procedures against Bush that could 
result in a lifetime ban from the thrift industry. Bush has denied any 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
